  "en_notes_asad": [
    {
      "note_no": "73",
      "note": "Lit., \"comes to pass against them\" - i.e., when the truth becomes obvious to them against all their expectations, and thus confounds them utterly: an allusion to the approach of the Last Hour, Resurrection and God's Judgment, all of which they were wont to regard as \"fables of ancient times\" (cf. verses 67-68 above). Alternatively, the phrase idha waqa'a al-qawi 'alayhim may be understood as \"when the sentence [of doom] is passed on them\", i.e., at the approach of the Last Hour, when it will be too late for repentance."
    },
    {
      "note_no": "74",
      "note": "The \"creature brought forth out of the earth\" is apparently an allegory of man's \"earthly\" outlook on life - in other words, the soul-destroying materialism characteristic of the time preceding the Last Hour. This \"creature\" parabolically \"tells\" men that their submergence in exclusively materialistic values - and, hence, their approaching self-destruction - is an outcome of their lack of belief in God. (See also 7:175-176 and the corresponding note 141.)"
    }
